<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="515" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1220,1643]" pageId="10" pageNumber="515">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1292,1318]" pageId="10" pageNumber="515">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gravely, F. H." box="[324,497,1292,1318]" pageId="10" pageNumber="515" pagination="211 - 282" refId="ref7267" refString="Gravely, F. H. (1931) Some Indian spiders of the families Ctenidae, Sparassidae, Selenopidae and Clubionidae. Records of the Indian Museum, Calcutta, 33, 211 - 282." type="journal article" year="1931">Gravely (1931)</bibRefCitation>
misidentified these specimens as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gravely" authorityYear="1931" box="[887,1015,1292,1318]" class="Arachnida" family="Liocranidae" genus="Sphingius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="10" pageNumber="515" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caniceps">
<emphasis box="[887,1015,1292,1318]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="515">S. caniceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and they do in fact belong to an undescribed 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1890" box="[266,376,1328,1354]" class="Arachnida" family="Liocranidae" genus="Sphingius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="10" pageNumber="515" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[266,376,1328,1354]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="515">Sphingius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. The female epigynum seems unique among other known female congeners, as it possesses inverted triangular postero-lateral epigynal margins separated medially from the anterior circular atrium by a transverse M-shaped plate (
<figureCitation box="[462,550,1400,1426]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1852,1876]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,187,1822]" captionTargetId="figure-23@12.[151,1436,181,1828]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 9. Sphingius sp.. A–D Ƌ left pedipalp: A prolateral, B ventral; C retrolateral; D enlarged view of retrolateral tibial apophysis, retrolateral. E ♀ epigynum, ventral. Abbreviations: C conductor, E embolus, MA median tegular apophysis, RTA retrolateral tibial apophysis, TA accessory tegular apophysis. Scale bars: A–E, 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4387697" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4387697/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="515">Fig. 9E</figureCitation>
). At present, a description of these specimens as a new species is difficult, due to the very poor condition and the genitalia are bleached, losing relevant diagnostic details, particularly those of the male. We therefore treat this species as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1890" box="[586,696,1472,1498]" class="Arachnida" family="Liocranidae" genus="Sphingius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="10" pageNumber="515" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[586,696,1472,1498]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="515">Sphingius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. until fresh specimens are available from Chennai. The ZSI collection has two glass bottles for this species named as “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gravely" authorityYear="1931" box="[766,891,1508,1534]" class="Arachnida" family="Liocranidae" genus="Sphingius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="10" pageNumber="515" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caniceps">
<emphasis box="[766,891,1508,1534]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="515">S. caniceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”, collected from Chennai. The first bottle (5751/ H2) contains a male and a female specimen in bad condition. The second bottle (5752/H2) is empty; the specimen(s) in this bottle may either be lost or perhaps loaned and not returned or misplaced elsewhere in the collection.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1220,1643]" box="[199,1150,1616,1643]" pageId="10" pageNumber="515">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,389,1616,1642]" pageId="10" pageNumber="515">Natural history.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1890" box="[396,506,1616,1642]" class="Arachnida" family="Liocranidae" genus="Sphingius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="10" pageNumber="515" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[396,506,1616,1642]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="515">Sphingius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. live among leaf litter, stones and soil (
<bibRefCitation author="Gravely, F. H." box="[979,1138,1616,1642]" pageId="10" pageNumber="515" pagination="211 - 282" refId="ref7267" refString="Gravely, F. H. (1931) Some Indian spiders of the families Ctenidae, Sparassidae, Selenopidae and Clubionidae. Records of the Indian Museum, Calcutta, 33, 211 - 282." type="journal article" year="1931">Gravely 1931</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
